04277nam a22007335i 9789048532056DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2017    ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485320567 a10.1515/97890485320562doi  a(DE-B1597)502569  a(OCoLC)1059284167  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aKorsten, Frans-Willem, eauthor.12aA Dutch Republican Baroque :bTheatricality, Dramatization, Moment and Event /cFrans-Willem Korsten. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b16 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmsterdam Studies in the Dutch Golden Age00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Republican baroque: a thunderclap, a city hall and two executions -- t2. The dramatic potential in history: Rome and the Republic - Grevius, Vondel, Knüpfer, and Job -- t3. The cruel death of worlds and political incompatibility - the brothers De Witt -- t4. A happy split of worlds or the comedic sublime - Frans Hals -- t5. The seas or the world as scene - Focquenbroch and Grotius -- t6. Not a frame but a lens: the touch of knowledge - Rumphius, Vossius, Spinoza -- t7. Public theater, collective drama and the new - Van den Enden and Huygens -- t8. Interrupting time for the sake of division: history and the tableau vivant - Rembrandt (Abraham and Isaac), Quast, Vondel, and Vos -- tList of illustrations -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tIndex of names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Dutch Republic in the Baroque era, two aesthetic formal modes, theater and drama, were dynamically related to two political concepts, event and moment. The Dutch version of the Baroque is characterized by a fascination with this world regarded as one possibility out of a plurality of potential worlds. It is this fascination that explains the coincidence in the Dutch Republic, strange at first sight, of Baroque exuberance, irregularity, paradox, and vertigo with scientific rigor, regularity, mathematical logic, and rational distance. In giving a new historical perspective on the Baroque as a specifically Dutch republican one, this study also offers a new and systematic approach to the interactions among the notions of theatricality, dramatization, moment, and event.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066731808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package 2017z978311066284908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press  eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060644740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048532056zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048532056.jpg  a978-3-11-060644-7  Amsterdam University Press  eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066284-9  AUP eBook Package 2017  a978-3-11-066731-8  AUP eBook Package 2016-2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG